By letter dated February 8, 1991, you requested our advice on behalf of Mayor George H. Waters and Councilmembers Michael R. Dalla,3 Jessie E. Van Deventer and Rosalie G. Zarate with respect to an amendment (Amendment III) of the community's redevelopment plan. These officials also serve as the chairman and members of the community's redevelopment agency and housing commission, the Community Development Commission of the City of National City (the "CDC"). Your request for advice and our response dated April 15, 1991 (See Eiser Advice Letter, No. A-91-098) listed the various economic interests of these public officials which we incorporate herein by reference.

The objectives of Amendment III were as follows:

1. Increasing the number of dollars of taxes which may be divided and allocated from $58 million to $250 million;

2. Increasing the amount of bonded indebtedness which can be outstanding from $18.2 million to $100 million;

3. Extending the duration of the provisions, requirements, and controls of the redevelopment plan from the year 2005 to the year 2015;

3 At this time you are not requesting advice regarding Councilmember Dalla and therefore we do not include him in our discussion. However, the discussion that follows is equally applicable to Councilmember Dalla's interest in a residence located within the redevelopment project.

4. Paying debt service on existing bonds ($1.7 million);

5. Making payments to other taxing agencies, namely, the County of San Diego, the National School District, and the Sweetwater Union High School District, probably through "pass-through" agreements (total approximate payments in excess of $8 million);

6. 20% set aside for low income housing;

7. Payment of overhead and administrative expenses;

8. Allocating the remaining funds one-half to neighborhood improvement, and one-half to commercial and industrial development;

9. Allowing payment by the CDC of part of the cost of acquiring land for and construction of a police facility.

At present, the actions needed to accomplish the redevelopment plan amendment have been completed. The city council and the CDC board are now about to consider implementation of certain actions made possible by Amendment III, such as the sale of tax allocation bonds, allocating funds to make neighborhood and industrial improvements in the community, approval of tax increment "pass through" agreements with other taxing agencies, and the expenditure of monies in the low and moderate income housing fund to benefit persons of low and moderate incomes.
